<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-11">
  <title>Resources for 9/11</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given a function <m>f</m> and an interval <m>[a, b]</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>, compute the <em>average rate of change</em> over the interval (i.e. compute <m>\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}</m>).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          In an applied problem, interpret what the average rate of change of the function means (e.g. if the input <m>x</m> is time and <m>f(x)</m> is the distance traveled at time <m>x</m>, then the average rate of change is velocity).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          In an applied problem, identify the units of the average rate of change (e.g. if the input <m>x</m> is time given in minutes and the function <m>f(x)</m> is the temperature given in <m>^\circ</m>F of an object at time <m>x</m> minutes, then the units of the average rate of change is <m>^\circ</m>F per minute).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the average rate of change to make predictions about the function.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-arc-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Introduction to Average Rate of Change (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>average rate of change</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="oFEmXq3kcr0" />

    <example>
      <title>Average Rate of Change (Velocity, Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        Complete the following average velocity problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              As you walk, your friend with a stopwatch takes down the following data.
            </p>
            <tabular halign="right">
              <row>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">Time (seconds)</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>1</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">2.5</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor">5.25</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="minor">Distance (feet)</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>-4</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">9</cell>
                <cell right="minor">16</cell>
                <cell right="minor">30</cell>
                <cell>40</cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If you had to describe the velocity between <m>t=3</m> and <m>t=5</m>, what would it be?  This is called the <em>average velocity</em>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the average velocity between <m>t=1</m> and <m>t=2.5</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find the average velocity between <m>t=1</m> and <m>t=5.25</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Assume the relationship between the time <m>t</m> and distance <m>d(t)</m> is <m>d(t)=t^2</m>, where <m>t</m> is time in seconds. Determine the average velocity between <m>t=2</m> seconds and
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>t=4</m> sec
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>t=3</m> sec.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>t=2.1</m> sec.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>t=0.5</m> sec.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>t=1.5</m> sec.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>t=1.9</m> sec.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>t=b</m> sec.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose the graph below is of time <m>t</m> versus distance <m>d(t)</m>.  What is the average velocity between <m>t=4</m> and <m>t=12</m>?
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
	            <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="velocity-graph-prep-2">
                <diagram dimensions="(300, 300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=(-3/8)*(x-3)^2+(27/8)</definition>
                  <definition>g(x)=(3/16)*(x-6)^2+2.25</definition>
                  <definition></definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-2,-1,15,12)">
                    <axes xlabel="t" ylabel="d(t)" hticks="(0,1,15)" vticks="(0,1,10)" />
                    <graph function="f" domain="(0,4)"/>
                    <graph function="g" domain="(4,15)" />
                    <line endpoints="((4,0),(4,3))" dash="8 8" />
                    <line endpoints="((0,3),(4,3))" dash="8 8" />
                    <line endpoints="((12,0),(12,9))" dash="8 8" />
                    <line endpoints="((0,9),(12,9))" dash="8 8" />
                    <point p="(4,3)" />
                    <point p="(12,9)" />
                  </coordinates>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If the distance traveled is <m>d(t)=t^2</m>, what is the average velocity between <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=b</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-application-arc">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities Applications of Averate Rate of Change</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>applications of average rate of change</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="xSzxTb-04eo" />

    <example>
      <title>Average Rate of Change (Application)</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following average rate of change application problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Jojo has a business selling mood rings (they'll be making a comeback!).  Jojo's data analyst claims that if Jojo sells a box of mood rings for a price $<m>p</m>, then they will be able to sell <m>d(p) = p^2-100p+2400</m> boxes of mood rings when <m>p</m> has a value between $0 and $40.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Determine the average rate of change of the number of boxes between the prices $10 and $30.  Make sure to include units in your answer.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What does the number you determined in (a) tell you about what will happen if Jojo changes their price?  Be as specific as you can.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What are the domain and range of the.function?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Jojo has been suffering from stress because of the pressure of the mood ring business.  Jojo now wears a device that measures blood pressure every 10 minutes.  Here are the readings of systolic pressure (i.e. the upper number in blood pressure) measured in millimeters of mercury (mmHg).
            </p>
            <tabular halign="right">
              <row>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">Time (minutes)</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>0</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">10</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">20</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">30</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">40</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">50</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor">60</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="minor">BP (mmHg)</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>105</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">112</cell>
                <cell right="minor">116</cell>
                <cell right="minor">122</cell>
                <cell right="minor">125</cell>
                <cell right="minor">129</cell>
                <cell>135</cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the average rate of change of blood pressure with respect to time between the beginning and end of the readings? Include units.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What does the number you computed above tell you about Jojo's blood pressure.  Be as specific as possible.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Based on the number you computed in (a), what do you expect Jojo's blood pressure to be after 68 minutes?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Based on the number you computed in (a), when would you expect Jojo's blood pressure to reach 150 mmHg?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

